{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_bowheadwhale_ver01/data/sn83045499/00514159567/1930041401/0712.xml":{"full_text":"Daily Alaska Empire\nJOHN W. TROY EDITOR AND MANAGER\nPublished every evening except Sunday by the\nEMPIRE PRINTING COMPANY at Second and Main\nStreets, Juneau, Alaska. _\nEntered in the Post Office In Juneau as Second Class\nmatter.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES.\nDelivered by carrier In Juneau, Douglas, Treadwell and\nThane for $1.25 per month.\nBy mall, postage paid, at the following rates:\nOne year, in advance, $12 00: six months, in advance,\n$6 00; one month, In advance, $1.26.\nSubscribers will confer a favor if they will promptly\nnotify the Business Office of any failure or Irregularity\nIn the delivery of their papers.\nTelephone for Editorial and Business Offices, 3(4.\nMEMBER OF ASSOCIATED PRESS.\nThe Associated Press is exclusively \u2022ntitled to the\nuse for republication of all news dispatches credited to\nIt or not otherwise credited in this paper and also the\nlocal news published herein.\nALASKA CIRCULATION GUARANTEED TO BE LARGER\nTHAN THAT OF ANY OTHER PUBLICATION.\nWASHINGTON\u2019S FORESTS MAKE\nPAYROLLS.\nWashington last\nI\nThe forests of the State of\nyear furnished almost one half of its industrial\npayrolls, according to statistics recently published;\nby the State Director of Labor and Industries.\nLumbering, mills of all types and allied activities j\nin 1929 paid $107,776,189 to its workmen.\nForest industries are easily one of Washington's\ngreatest sources of wealth. And they are growing\nrather than declining, as was evidenced by the fact\nthat last year wages paid to workers were $5,170,-j.\n523 in excess of those for 1928. i\nAlaska\u2019s forest resources, virtually untouched,; i\nhave within them the same elements for pros\nperity for the Territory that Washington is realizing\nfrom hers. With the development of the pulp and\npaper industry here, promised definitely for the j\nnear future, millions of dollars will be put into I,\ncirculation in the shape of wages for labor, trans- j<\nportation, purchase of supplies, financial returns to\nthe Territorial treasury from the stumpage fees for 1\ntimber, and in other ways.\nIn fact, the establishment of two such large,1\npaper manufacturing plants as are proposed for1\nKetchikan and Juneau bids fair to remake the j\nIndustrial map of Southeastern Alaska. In them-!,\nselves they will give steady employment to almost i\nas many workmen as now are required in all save\nseasonal industries. Allied industries, certain to Ji\nfollow the pulp and paper makers, will add mater- ,1\nially to this, and the payroll envelope of this distrist\nwill be very largely augmented.\nVery different would be the case if shipment\nof raw materials were permitted to be made to j\npoints without the Territory. Efforts to export\nlogs to foreign manufacturers have been very prop\nerly combatted by the United States Forest Service.\nWashington today would be receiving but very little\nbenefit from its forests if its logs were shipped to\nCalifornia, Japan or British Columbia for manu\nfacture. And Alaska would get even less from its\nforests once a policy of exporting logs were estab\nlished.\nINDUSTRIAL CONVALESCENCE\nPROCEEDING NORMALLY.\nNotwithstanding encouraging operations in the\nI steel, electrical, railroad and farm equipment indus\ntries and a few others the 1930 business revival to\ndate has been of modest proportions. Comparison\nwith normal figures indicates that recovery has in\nsome respects been less than seasonal.\nIt becomes more apparept as the year progresses\nthat notwithstanding rigid inventory control so\ni called that production in 1929 was far beyond the\nability of the consuming public to absorb. In other\nwords, there was unmistakable overconsumption\nthough whether it was brought about by growth of\ninstalment buying or extravagance is not clear.\nThus, it is taking time to work off surplus sup\nplies of goods and the process has been complicated\nby the persistent decline in commodity prices. So\nrigorous, however, has been the curtailment of pro\nduction that a healthy ratio between current de\nmand and supply is gradually being established that\nshould permit of more active revival as 1930 grows\nolder.\nThe oil industry has solved its acute problem\napparently and other industries are likely to have\nequal success. The program may spell an \u201coff\nyear\" in certain directions, but it bids fair to pre\nvent anything resembling a real business depression.\nAfter the industrial convalescence is completed\u2014and\nit should be hastened by the constructive efforts j\nof the Government\u2014the way should be cleared for\nbroader business revival.\nFloating Medical Unit.\n(Anchorage Times.)\nThe importance of the mobile medical service\nof the office of education along the Yukon River\nand its tributaries having been very convincingly\niemonstrated during the last several seasons, thought\nshould now be given to putting the service on a\noermanent basis, with adequate facilities for carry\nng on the steadily expanding work. There appears\n,o be very urgent need of a new boat to replace\nhe unseaworthy craft with which the work has\naeen carried on since the inauguration of the serv\nce three seasons ago.\nThe history of the Martha Angeline is fairly\nveil known to most oldtlmers along the Yukon,\nrhe boat was built about eighteen years ago for\nise as a freighter on the Innoko River and it also\nerved as a fish carrier for the Kearns cannery\nin the lower Yukon before coming into the pos\nession of the Government. It was remodeled, of\nourse, to meet the requirements of a medical boat\nlut the old hull was not designed for the kind of\nvork it is now doing and the lives of those on\nloard are endangered whenever the craft ventures\nnto the wide expanses of the lower Yukon, where\nough water frequently is encoountered. The deck\ntands less than two feet above the water and\n/hen storms occur it is necessary to make a run I\nor shelter to escape foundering. There is much J\ntormy weather along the lower river during the\nourse of a season and much valuable time there-1\nore is lost while the boat is in shelter awaiting j\nhe return of smooth water. A seaworthy craft,\nmilt especially for service on the river, would i\nnable the medical relief to be expanded greatly\n,\u2019lthout materially increasing the cost, and in view\nif the splendid results thus far obtained with the j\nnadequate outfit now in use, the investment in\nlew equipment would appear to be fully justified j\n,\u2019ithout further delay.\nThe mobile medical unit is the only medical i\nid available to the hundreds of natives and whites j\ncattered along the lower Yukon and the service j\nproving so helpful to them that the service j\nhould be expanded to the fullest possible limit,\n\u2019hat can only be done by providing the medical j\ntaff with safe transport and a properly equipped\nessel.\nLos Angeles Times advises the authorities there\no lock the gates against the influx of Chicago I\n,nd Detroit gangsters. But that won\u2019t do any good.\n\u2019hose birds from Chicago and Detroit will take j j\nate and all.\u2014(Macon, Ga., Telegraph.)\nB\nGlean a\u00bb& Saint Ofo\nRear this^e people. Chink jlct 11\nfUiotD ail jften, Women anil Cbil&ren\nttjesc ^refients:\nrHAT, WhereA. the NATIONAL CLEAN UP AND PAINT UP\nCAMPAIGN ha\u00ab resulted in many advantages to community life through\nout the United States,\nIn safeguarding HEALTH;\nIn promoting THRIFT;\nIn furthering FIRE PREVENTION\nIn stimulating CIVIC PRIDE; and\nIn making the HOME AND CITY BEAUTIFUL;\nNOW, THEREFORE, Be it known that plans have been\nperfected for a thorough CLEAN UP AND PAINT UP CAM\nPAIGN in JUNEAU, ALASKA, beginning APRIL 15TH. This\ndate to mark the Opening of a real campaign of persistent and\nconstructive effort in cleaning up and KEEPING IT UP. In\nthis worthy movement of Cleaning. Painting, Planting, Repair\ning and general Rehabilitation and Beautification we urge each\ncitizen to do his or her best part to make our community\nClean, Healthy, Thrifty\nSafe and Beautiful\nTHOMAS JUDSON, Mayor\nHARRY WATSON, President,\nChamber of Commerce\n-IMD\n/^HfH'UjyuwQr\n<_ 0F J^ZZ PlANO\nLearn the Modern Way\nPlay Real Jazz Piano\nin 3 Months\nOur representative in Juneau\nuntil May 15. Call 1534 for\nFREE DEMONSTRATION or\nwrite Temple of Music, Ta-!\ncoma, Washington.\nl\nI\nI\nCANDY FOR EASTER\nH. R. SHEPARD\nSON, Inc.\nGENERAL INSURANCE\n\u201cAbsolute Security\u201d\nValentine Euilding\nH II I I hM I I I M-l I I I i 1 f\n:Ruy the best, fresh from the\nfactory,\nJOHNSTON'S\nI\n\u2014at\u2014\nPhone Zi We Deliver\nThe Nyal Service Drug Store\nSPECIAL EASTER\nSALE j'\nMarten\nM ink\nFox\nNeck Pieces\nY urman\u2019s\nJUNIOR\nDIAMOND\nBRIQUETS\nARE\nJUST RIGHT\nFOR THE\nPARLOR\nFURNACE\ni l\nr\nW. P. Johnson\nFRIG1DAIRE\nDELCO LIGHT PRODUCTS\nMAYTAG WASHING\nMACHINES\nDAY-FAN RADIOS\nPhone 1\nFront Street Juneau\nr\nOld papers ai Trie Empire or\ni 'Ice.\nj PROFESSIONAL\nt\nI f\nHelene W. L. Albrecht I\nPHT8IOTHERAPT\nMassage, Electricity, Infra Red\nRev, Medical Gymnastics.\n4lu Goldstein Buildlnp;\nPhone Office, 216\ng\nj\" DRS. KASElt FREEBTJRGEHU\nDENTISTS\n301-303 Goldstein Bldg.\nPHONE 56\nHours 9 a. m. to B p. m.\n-----41\nDr. Charles P. Jenne\nDENTIST\nRooms 8 and 9 Valentine\nBuilding\nTelephone 176\n----\u2014-4;\nDr. A. W. Stewart\nDENTIST\nHours 9 a. m. to 6 p. m.\nSEWARD BUILDING\nOffice Phone 669, Res.\nPhone 276\n\u2022i ---n\nDr. H. \\ance\nOsteopath\u2014201 Goldstein Bldg.\nHours: 10 to 12; 1 to 5; 7 to\nor by appointment\nLicensed Osteopathic Physician i\nPhone: Office 1671.\nj Residence, MacKinnon Apts. I\n!*rs\nDr. Geo. L. Barton\nCHIROPRACTOR\nHellenthal Building\nOFFICE SERVICE ONLY\nHours: 10 a. m. to 12 noon\n2 p. m. to 5 p. m.\n6 p. m. to 8 p. m.\nBy Appointment\nPHONE 259\n-a\nRobert Simpson\nOpt. D.\nGraduate kps Angeles Col\nlege of Optometry and\nOpthalmology\nGl